WEBVTT

00:04.600 --> 00:11.680
Oxford Bookworms, Stage 1. The Coldest Place on Earth, by

00:11.680 --> 00:12.740
Tim Vickery.

00:13.520 --> 00:19.120
Read by Mark Straker. Published in copyright, Oxford University Press,

00:19.820 --> 00:20.340
1997.

00:23.040 --> 00:30.120
Chapter 1. Two Ships. The Race began in the summer

00:30.120 --> 00:37.460
of 1910. On June 1st, in London, a black ship,

00:38.260 --> 00:42.680
the Terra Nova, went down the river Thames to the

00:42.680 --> 00:48.180
sea. Thousands of people stood by the river to

00:48.180 --> 00:56.920
watch it. They were all excited and happy. On the

00:56.920 --> 01:02.020
Terra Nova, Captain Robert Falcon Scott smiled

01:02.020 --> 01:10.080
quietly. It was a very important day for him. He

01:10.080 --> 01:18.160
was a strong man, not very tall, in the blue

01:18.160 --> 01:23.000
ship. He was 41 years old. But he had a

01:23.000 --> 01:29.460
young face, like a boy. His eyes were dark and

01:29.460 --> 01:29.880
quiet.

01:32.520 --> 01:38.360
One man on the ship, Titus Oates, smiled at Scott.

01:40.260 --> 01:45.940
What an exciting day, Captain, he said. Look at

01:45.940 --> 01:53.820
those people. I feel like an important man. Scott laughed.

01:55.100 --> 01:58.480
You are important, Titus, he said.

01:59.660 --> 02:04.640
And you're going to be famous, too. We all are.

02:06.060 --> 02:15.920
Do you see this flag? He looked at the big

02:15.920 --> 02:23.540
notes. That flag is coming with us, he said. In

02:23.540 --> 02:27.140
the Antarctic, I'm going to carry it under my

02:27.140 --> 02:32.420
clothes. We're going to be the first men at the

02:32.420 --> 02:36.860
South Pole. And that flag is going to be first,

02:36.860 --> 02:46.460
too. Five days later, on June 6th, a man opened

02:46.460 --> 02:49.420
the door of his wooden house in Norway.

02:51.480 --> 02:57.200
He was a tall man with a long face. He

02:57.200 --> 03:06.840
waited outside the house for a minute. Everything was very

03:07.520 --> 03:16.000
only mountains, trees, and water. It was nearly dark. The

03:16.000 --> 03:18.240
sky was black over the mountains.

03:21.180 --> 03:25.200
The man smiled and walked quickly away from the house,

03:26.160 --> 03:27.160
down to the sea.

03:29.120 --> 03:33.720
In the water, a big wooden ship waited for him.

03:35.780 --> 03:39.620
The man got onto the ship and talked and laughed

03:39.620 --> 03:47.140
quietly with his friends. The ship's name was Fram. And

03:47.140 --> 03:52.340
the man was Ruhold Amundsen. The Fram

03:52.340 --> 03:56.560
was the most beautiful ship on Earth, Amundsen thought.

03:59.000 --> 04:05.160
His friends were the best skiers on Earth, too. One

04:05.160 --> 04:07.580
of them, Ulaftbioland,

04:08.480 --> 04:15.500
smiled at him. North Pole, here we come, Captain. He

04:15.500 --> 04:15.700
said,

04:16.700 --> 04:22.780
Yes, Amundsen said. His friends could not see his face

04:22.780 --> 04:28.000
in the dark. Fram is going to the Arctic.

04:30.880 --> 04:34.340
Everyone on the Fram was ready to go to the

04:34.340 --> 04:36.480
North Pole to the Arctic.

04:38.660 --> 04:44.540
Amundsen wanted to go there, too. But first, he wanted

04:44.540 --> 04:49.640
to go south. His friends didn't know that.

04:50.960 --> 04:57.080
At midnight, on June 6th, the Fram moved quietly away

04:57.080 --> 05:01.180
from Amundsen's house, out to sea.

05:10.260 --> 05:13.320
Chapter 2 The Race

05:15.490 --> 05:19.120
The Fram went to an island in the south of

05:19.120 --> 05:24.560
Norway. It was a very little island with only one

05:24.560 --> 05:31.280
small wooden house, two trees, and nearly a hundred dogs.

05:32.600 --> 05:38.480
Look at that, the Orland said. It's an island of

05:38.480 --> 05:43.360
dogs. There are dogs in the water, near the trees,

05:44.240 --> 05:50.720
on the house, dogs everywhere. Two men came out of

05:50.720 --> 05:51.100
the house.

05:52.780 --> 05:58.700
Harsal, Lindstrom, Amundsen said. It's good to see you.

05:59.770 --> 06:04.600
How many dogs do you have for me? 99, Roald

06:04.600 --> 06:08.960
said Harsal, the best 99 dogs from Greenland.

06:10.180 --> 06:14.880
And they're very happy. They don't work. They just eat

06:14.880 --> 06:19.180
and play all day. They're having a wonderful

06:19.180 --> 06:26.360
summer here. Good, good, Amundsen laughed. But that's finished now.

06:27.420 --> 06:33.060
Hey, Yourland, stop laughing. Come down here and help me.

06:33.960 --> 06:36.500
Let's get all these dogs onto the ship.

06:38.300 --> 06:42.860
It was not easy. The dogs were fat and strong,

06:43.600 --> 06:46.100
and they didn't want to go on the ship.

06:47.540 --> 06:53.320
But at last, after three hours' hard work, all 99

06:53.320 --> 06:58.100
were on the ship. And the fram went out to

06:58.100 --> 06:58.580
see again.

07:00.660 --> 07:06.040
The men were not happy. The weather was bad. The

07:06.040 --> 07:10.320
dogs were dirty. And some of the men were ill.

07:10.320 --> 07:13.540
They began to ask questions.

07:14.920 --> 07:19.380
Why are we bringing dogs with us, asked one man,

07:19.540 --> 07:20.060
Johansson?

07:21.520 --> 07:26.440
We're going thousands of kilometers south past Cape Horn and

07:26.440 --> 07:27.720
then north to Alaska.

07:29.400 --> 07:32.660
Why not wait and to get dogs in Alaska?

07:34.380 --> 07:40.120
Don't ask me, said his friend, Helma Honson. I don't

07:40.120 --> 07:40.840
understand it.

07:42.720 --> 07:48.200
The men talked for a long time. Then, on September

07:48.200 --> 07:52.200
9th, Amundsen called everyone to the back of the ship.

07:53.480 --> 07:59.280
He stood quietly and looked at them. Behind him was

07:59.280 --> 07:59.960
a big map.

08:00.700 --> 08:05.760
It was not a map of the Arctic. It was

08:05.760 --> 08:07.300
a map of Antarctica.

08:09.660 --> 08:15.860
The Orland looked at Helma Honson and laughed. Then Amundsen

08:15.860 --> 08:17.000
began to speak.

08:18.660 --> 08:25.800
Boys, he said, I know you are unhappy. You often

08:25.800 --> 08:30.140
ask me difficult questions and I don't answer.

08:31.640 --> 08:37.820
Well, I'm going to answer all those questions now, today.

08:37.820 --> 08:43.600
We began to work for this journey two years ago.

08:44.640 --> 08:48.880
Then, we wanted to be the first men at the

08:48.880 --> 08:49.600
North Pole.

08:50.900 --> 08:56.540
But last year, Perry and American found the North Pole.

08:58.060 --> 09:03.700
So, America was first to the North Pole, not Norway.

09:05.120 --> 09:08.540
We're going there, but we're too late.

09:10.780 --> 09:16.940
I don't understand this, the Orland thought. Why is Amundsen

09:16.940 --> 09:18.960
talking about the North Pole,

09:19.860 --> 09:22.600
with a map of Antarctica behind him?

09:24.760 --> 09:29.140
Amundsen stopped for a minute and looked at all the

09:29.140 --> 09:29.960
men slowly.

09:31.420 --> 09:33.460
No one said anything.

09:35.520 --> 09:40.280
We have to go a long way south before we

09:40.280 --> 09:42.380
get to Alaska, he said.

09:43.580 --> 09:46.480
Very near Antarctica, you know.

09:47.800 --> 09:53.240
And Captain Scott, the Englishman, is going to the South

09:53.240 --> 09:54.600
Pole this year.

09:55.780 --> 09:58.400
He wants to put his British flag there.

09:58.880 --> 10:03.900
An American flag at the North Pole, a British flag

10:03.900 --> 10:05.520
at the South Pole.

10:07.080 --> 10:09.640
The Orland began to understand.

10:11.180 --> 10:16.300
He started to smile and couldn't stop. He was warm

10:16.300 --> 10:17.400
and excited.

10:19.780 --> 10:23.700
Well, boys, Amundsen said slowly.

10:24.800 --> 10:27.540
Do we want the British to put their flag at

10:27.540 --> 10:28.820
the South Pole first?

10:30.120 --> 10:32.120
How fast can we travel?

10:33.580 --> 10:37.240
We have a lot of dogs and some of the

10:37.240 --> 10:39.400
most wonderful skiers on earth.

10:40.720 --> 10:43.200
The Orland here is the best in Norway.

10:43.840 --> 10:48.160
So, I have an idea, boys.

10:49.280 --> 10:54.240
Let's go to the South Pole and put the Norwegian

10:54.240 --> 10:57.340
flag there before the British.

10:58.220 --> 10:59.960
What do you say?

11:01.860 --> 11:05.860
For a minute or two, it was very quiet.

11:07.220 --> 11:11.780
Amundsen waited, and the men watched him and thought.

11:13.700 --> 11:15.260
Then the Orland laughed.

11:16.780 --> 11:19.680
Yes, he said. Why not?

11:20.680 --> 11:24.640
It's a ski race, isn't it? And the English can't

11:24.640 --> 11:24.880
ski.

11:25.760 --> 11:31.120
It's a wonderful idea. Of course. Let's go.

11:40.240 --> 11:43.620
Chapter 3. The ponies

11:46.380 --> 11:53.000
On October 27, the Terranova arrived in Wellington, New Zealand.

11:54.640 --> 11:59.740
When Scott came off the ship, a newspaperman walked up

11:59.740 --> 12:00.140
to him.

12:01.400 --> 12:05.960
Captain Scott, Captain Scott, can I talk to you, please?

12:06.980 --> 12:07.340
He said.

12:09.060 --> 12:10.640
Scott stopped and smiled.

12:11.700 --> 12:16.620
Yes, of course, he said. What do you want to

12:16.620 --> 12:16.840
know?

12:18.380 --> 12:21.440
Are you going to win? The man asked.

12:22.220 --> 12:24.580
When? Scott asked.

12:25.980 --> 12:26.620
When what?

12:28.080 --> 12:32.700
When the race to the South Pole, of course, the

12:32.700 --> 12:33.820
newspaperman said.

12:35.180 --> 12:40.280
It's a race between you and Amundsen now. Look at

12:40.280 --> 12:40.520
this.

12:42.020 --> 12:46.680
He gave a newspaper to Scott. Scott looked at it.

12:46.680 --> 12:48.620
It said,

12:49.780 --> 12:52.940
Fram Brace's Scott to South Pole.

12:54.140 --> 12:57.300
We're going to win, says Amundsen.

12:59.460 --> 13:01.460
Scott's face went white.

13:02.820 --> 13:05.380
Give me that, he said.

13:06.760 --> 13:09.800
He took the newspaper and read it carefully.

13:11.320 --> 13:14.820
The newspaperman watched him and waited.

13:16.680 --> 13:19.900
Well, Captain Scott, he said at blast.

13:20.960 --> 13:24.800
Who's going to win this race? Tell me that.

13:26.940 --> 13:32.560
Scott looked at him angrily. This is stupid, he said.

13:33.460 --> 13:34.540
It's not a race.

13:35.500 --> 13:41.200
I came here to learn about the Antarctic. I'm not

13:41.200 --> 13:44.900
interested in Amundsen, or in races.

13:46.680 --> 13:50.740
Then he walked back onto his ship with the newspaper

13:50.740 --> 13:52.020
in his hand.

13:54.680 --> 14:00.760
Later that day, he talked to his men. He gave

14:00.760 --> 14:03.140
them the newspaper and laughed.

14:04.740 --> 14:10.180
It doesn't matter, he said. We're in front of Amundsen,

14:10.900 --> 14:14.480
and we have more men and more money.

14:15.400 --> 14:19.500
He has only eight men and a lot of dogs.

14:20.960 --> 14:26.060
I know about dogs. They don't work in the Antarctic.

14:27.640 --> 14:33.200
We have 16 men and the new motor sledges. They

14:33.200 --> 14:34.080
are much better.

14:35.420 --> 14:40.700
And tomorrow the ponies are coming. We need ponies, motor

14:40.700 --> 14:44.240
sledges, and good strong British men.

14:45.140 --> 14:50.900
That's all. Forget about Amundsen. He's not important.

14:53.440 --> 14:58.800
Scott asked oats to look after the ponies, but he

14:58.800 --> 15:00.840
did not let oats buy them.

15:02.260 --> 15:07.260
When oats first saw the ponies in New Zealand, he

15:07.260 --> 15:12.380
was very unhappy. Most of the ponies were old,

15:12.380 --> 15:15.300
and some of them were ill.

15:17.240 --> 15:23.020
They're beautiful ponies, Titus, Scott said. They come from China.

15:24.100 --> 15:25.940
They're wonderful ponies.

15:27.840 --> 15:32.220
Oats looked at them angrily and said nothing.

15:34.260 --> 15:38.860
Then he asked, where is their food, Captain?

15:39.800 --> 15:47.700
Yeah, Scott opened a door. Oats looked inside. He thought

15:47.700 --> 15:48.440
for a minute.

15:50.280 --> 15:55.680
We need more food than this, Captain Scott. These ponies

15:55.680 --> 16:00.140
are going to work in the coldest place on earth.

16:00.860 --> 16:05.640
They need a lot of food, more than this.

16:07.540 --> 16:13.240
Scott smiled quietly. We can't take more food on this

16:13.240 --> 16:17.080
ship, Titus. Where can we put it?

16:17.860 --> 16:23.100
But it doesn't matter, old boy. They're very strong ponies,

16:23.720 --> 16:27.540
you know. The best ponies on earth.

16:29.960 --> 16:34.360
Later that night, oats wrote a letter to his mother.

16:36.240 --> 16:40.980
There are 19 ponies on the Terranova now, he wrote.

16:42.380 --> 16:46.240
All the ponies are in a small room at the

16:46.240 --> 16:47.240
front of the ship.

16:48.580 --> 16:52.780
We eat our food in the room under the ponies,

16:53.240 --> 16:57.140
so our table is often wet and dirty.

16:59.080 --> 17:03.060
Scott makes a lot of mistakes, I think.

17:04.540 --> 17:09.120
And Antarctica is a very dangerous place.

17:17.620 --> 17:19.540
Chapter 4

17:20.620 --> 17:22.120
Food Depos

17:23.740 --> 17:28.040
The two ships, Terranova and Fram,

17:28.980 --> 17:35.700
arrived in Antarctica in January 1911, at the end of

17:35.700 --> 17:36.000
summer.

17:36.000 --> 17:42.280
The Englishmen and the Norwegians wanted to stay on the

17:42.280 --> 17:43.980
ice all winter.

17:45.220 --> 17:48.340
They wanted to be ready to go to the south

17:48.340 --> 17:52.580
pole at the beginning of the next Antarctic summer.

17:54.500 --> 18:00.600
The dogs pulled the Norwegians sledges. They rang quickly over

18:00.600 --> 18:01.080
the snow,

18:01.820 --> 18:05.760
and pulled the big sledges from the ship onto the

18:05.760 --> 18:10.420
ice. The men ran beside them on skis.

18:12.540 --> 18:18.000
They put a big wooden house on the ice. The

18:18.000 --> 18:22.600
house was full of food and skis and sledges.

18:23.540 --> 18:26.420
They called it Framheim.

18:28.850 --> 18:33.540
Outside the house, the dogs lived in holes under the

18:33.540 --> 18:33.900
snow.

18:36.370 --> 18:40.660
When the house was ready, the men made their first

18:40.660 --> 18:41.880
journey south.

18:44.020 --> 18:48.720
Before the winter, they wanted to take a lot of

18:48.720 --> 18:52.980
food south, and leave it in depots.

18:54.760 --> 18:59.060
For the long journey to the pole, they needed a

18:59.060 --> 19:03.600
lot of food, and they couldn't carry it all with

19:03.600 --> 19:03.820
them.

19:05.720 --> 19:13.960
On February 10th, five men, three sledges, 18 dogs, and

19:13.960 --> 19:19.340
half a ton of food left Framheim and went south.

19:21.420 --> 19:25.580
It was easy. The weather was warm for the Antarctic

19:25.580 --> 19:30.380
between minus 7 degrees centigrade and minus 17

19:30.380 --> 19:36.860
degrees centigrade. The snow was good, and the dogs and

19:36.860 --> 19:38.380
skis went fast.

19:40.260 --> 19:46.820
They went 50 or 60 kilometers every day. After four

19:46.820 --> 19:51.880
days, they reached 80 degrees south and made

19:51.880 --> 19:53.240
the first depot.

19:56.900 --> 20:02.400
Amundsen made his depot very carefully. It was very important

20:02.400 --> 20:05.420
to find it again next summer.

20:06.880 --> 20:12.400
So he put a big black flag on top. Then

20:12.400 --> 20:15.920
he put 10 flags to the east of the depot.

20:15.920 --> 20:23.080
Each flag, half a kilometer from the next, and 10

20:23.080 --> 20:24.420
flags to the west.

20:25.940 --> 20:30.480
So there were flags for five kilometers to the left

20:30.480 --> 20:34.660
of the depot and five kilometers to the right.

20:37.340 --> 20:42.200
Then they went back to Framheim and took some more

20:42.200 --> 20:43.060
food south.

20:43.940 --> 20:52.200
This time to 82 degrees south. This time it was

20:52.200 --> 20:59.400
harder. The temperature was sometimes minus 40 degrees centigrade,

21:00.380 --> 21:04.060
and there were strong winds with a lot of snow.

21:05.020 --> 21:08.540
The dogs and men were very tired,

21:08.540 --> 21:15.280
and the tents and boots were bad. At the second

21:15.280 --> 21:20.020
depot, they put out 60 flags to help them find

21:20.020 --> 21:20.500
it again.

21:22.700 --> 21:28.560
They came back to Framheim on March 23rd. It was

21:28.560 --> 21:31.980
nearly winter in the Antarctic. Their ship,

21:31.980 --> 21:38.460
Fram, was far away now, near South America. They were

21:38.460 --> 21:40.120
alone on the ice.

21:42.540 --> 21:47.000
Oats went with Scott to make the first British depot.

21:48.820 --> 21:53.200
They left Cape Evans on January 25th.

21:54.080 --> 22:01.960
There were 13 men, 8 ponies, and 26 dogs. The

22:01.960 --> 22:05.980
dogs were faster than the ponies. They ran quickly

22:05.980 --> 22:10.360
over the top of the snow, but the ponies' feet

22:10.360 --> 22:15.880
went through it. Every morning, the ponies started

22:15.880 --> 22:22.120
first, and the dogs started two hours later, because they

22:22.120 --> 22:23.040
ran faster.

22:25.040 --> 22:29.260
At night, the dogs made warm holes under the snow,

22:29.880 --> 22:33.300
but the ponies stood on top of the snow.

22:34.820 --> 22:38.120
It was minus 20 degrees centigrade.

22:39.540 --> 22:46.060
After 15 days, oats talked to Scott. There was a

22:46.060 --> 22:50.440
strong wind, and the two men's faces were white with

22:50.440 --> 22:50.780
snow.

22:53.330 --> 22:59.240
Three of the ponies are ill, Captain, oats said. They

22:59.240 --> 23:00.420
can't go on.

23:02.120 --> 23:08.720
Don't be stupid, oats, Scott answered. They're good, strong animals.

23:09.800 --> 23:11.460
The best ponies on earth.

23:12.740 --> 23:20.340
Not these three, oats said. They're ill and unhappy, and

23:20.340 --> 23:24.940
now they can't walk. Let's kill them and leave

23:24.940 --> 23:29.080
the meat here in the snow. We can eat it,

23:29.500 --> 23:30.820
or the dogs can.

23:32.210 --> 23:38.260
Of course not, Scott said angrily. These ponies are our

23:38.260 --> 23:41.000
friends. They work hard for us.

23:41.820 --> 23:49.820
I don't kill my friends. Three days later, two of

23:49.820 --> 23:51.060
the ponies were dead.

23:52.880 --> 23:58.840
Scott's men were slower than Amundsons. It took them 24

23:58.840 --> 24:01.900
days to get to 80 degrees south.

24:03.380 --> 24:08.460
They made a big depot there, and put one large

24:08.460 --> 24:13.320
black flag on top of it. Then they went back

24:13.320 --> 24:14.380
to Cape Evans.

24:16.600 --> 24:21.360
Their camp was on an island in the ice, and

24:21.360 --> 24:26.380
the sea ice moved sometimes. There were holes in the

24:26.380 --> 24:29.820
ice and black sea water under it.

24:31.660 --> 24:36.620
One day, seven ponies went through the ice into the

24:36.620 --> 24:38.400
sea and died.

24:40.040 --> 24:43.880
One motor sledge also went into the sea.

24:54.400 --> 24:58.540
Chapter 5 A Long Cold Winter

25:00.580 --> 25:06.320
It was dark for four months. Outside the wooden house

25:06.320 --> 25:07.480
at Framheim,

25:08.400 --> 25:15.480
it was often minus 60 degrees centigrade. The dogs lived

25:15.480 --> 25:17.960
in warm holes under the snow.

25:19.280 --> 25:23.400
The men stayed in the house and worked in their

25:23.400 --> 25:24.920
rooms under the snow.

25:27.470 --> 25:31.580
The skis and sledges came from the best shops in

25:31.580 --> 25:35.500
Norway, but Beorland wasn't happy with them.

25:36.460 --> 25:40.300
He changed a lot of things on the skis and

25:40.300 --> 25:45.700
sledges. Soon, the sledges were stronger than before.

25:47.180 --> 25:53.680
The skis were better and faster too. All the Norwegians

25:53.680 --> 25:57.760
worked hard. They looked after their dogs

25:58.400 --> 26:05.920
and worked on their equipment. The sledges, skis, tents. Every

26:05.920 --> 26:07.960
day, they thought about their

26:07.960 --> 26:13.240
journey to the pole and talked about it. And every

26:13.240 --> 26:16.260
day, Amundsen thought about Scott.

26:17.680 --> 26:22.420
One day, in mid-winter, he talked to his men.

26:24.540 --> 26:32.020
Let's start early before Scott, Amundsen said. Remember, Scott has

26:32.020 --> 26:33.040
more men than us,

26:33.880 --> 26:38.880
and he has motor sledges too. Perhaps, they can go

26:38.880 --> 26:42.540
faster than us. Beorland laughed.

26:43.460 --> 26:47.500
Oh no, they can't go faster than me, he said.

26:48.420 --> 26:52.280
On snow, nothing can go faster than a good man

26:52.280 --> 26:59.800
on skis. We don't know, Amundsen said. You're the best

26:59.800 --> 27:02.720
skier in Norway, but you get tired,

27:03.360 --> 27:09.280
and dogs get tired too. Motor sledges don't get tired.

27:10.000 --> 27:11.640
They can go all day

27:11.640 --> 27:19.500
and all night. You, Hansen, laughed angrily. That's stupid, he

27:19.500 --> 27:19.720
said.

27:20.700 --> 27:24.560
Perhaps the motor sledges can go all night, but the

27:24.560 --> 27:26.240
Englishmen can't.

27:27.400 --> 27:33.920
The English can't win, Roald. They don't understand snow, but

27:33.920 --> 27:37.840
we do. And they're too slow.

27:39.400 --> 27:44.640
Perhaps, Amundsen said, but I want to win this race.

27:45.620 --> 27:50.380
So, we're going to start early. Do you understand?

27:51.820 --> 27:58.240
It was quiet and warm inside Framheim. Beorland looked at

27:58.240 --> 28:00.860
Amundsen and thought about the long,

28:01.580 --> 28:06.400
cold journey in front of him. He thought about the

28:06.400 --> 28:07.520
dogs in their holes,

28:07.520 --> 28:12.320
under the snow, and listened to the wind over the

28:12.320 --> 28:12.560
house.

28:15.040 --> 28:22.920
When, Roald, he said quietly, on August 24th, the sun

28:22.920 --> 28:27.080
comes back on that day. We start then.

28:28.400 --> 28:34.740
But we can't, you Hansen said. He looked angry and

28:34.740 --> 28:40.280
unhappy. That's too early. We can't start then.

28:41.100 --> 28:48.540
It's dangerous and stupid. Amundsen looked at you Hansen coldly.

28:49.420 --> 28:54.980
You're wrong, you Hansen, he said. We want to win,

28:55.480 --> 29:00.040
remember? So we start on August 24th.

29:01.600 --> 29:05.400
Beorland listened to the winter wind outside.

29:08.580 --> 29:13.880
In Scott's camp at Cape Evans, no one talked about

29:13.880 --> 29:17.440
Amundsen and no one worked hard.

29:19.020 --> 29:22.820
They had good food and they played football on the

29:22.820 --> 29:23.060
snow.

29:24.780 --> 29:30.100
They wrote a newspaper, the South Polar Times, and read

29:30.100 --> 29:30.460
books.

29:32.300 --> 29:35.800
No one learned to ski, no one worked on the

29:35.800 --> 29:40.860
motor sledges. Twice, men went for long journeys

29:40.860 --> 29:46.100
across the snow. They walked and pulled the sledges themselves.

29:47.420 --> 29:49.260
Oats stayed at Cape Evans

29:49.810 --> 29:55.540
and looked after his ponies. Over the window in Cape

29:55.540 --> 29:58.840
Evans, Scott put a map of Antarctica.

30:00.360 --> 30:04.360
With a pen, he made a line from Cape Evans

30:04.360 --> 30:08.540
to the South Pole, and he put a little British

30:08.540 --> 30:08.900
flag

30:08.900 --> 30:14.940
at the pole. Under the map, Scott wrote the day

30:14.940 --> 30:17.000
for the start of their journey.

30:18.360 --> 30:22.800
We start on November 3rd, he wrote.

30:30.960 --> 30:34.240
Chapter 6 A Bad Start

30:36.700 --> 30:42.720
On August 23rd, the Norwegian sledges were ready. They took

30:42.720 --> 30:45.900
them outside and the dogs pulled them

30:45.900 --> 30:50.080
out of the ice. The sun came up for half

30:50.080 --> 30:55.740
an hour, but it was too cold, minus 46 degrees

30:55.740 --> 31:02.140
centigrade. They could not travel in that weather. They went

31:02.140 --> 31:04.340
back to Franheim and waited.

31:06.560 --> 31:14.220
They waited two weeks until September 8th. Then, with the

31:14.220 --> 31:16.820
temperature at minus 37 degrees centigrade,

31:17.880 --> 31:23.200
they started. They ran happily across the snow to the

31:23.200 --> 31:29.160
South. Eight men, seven sledges, and 86 dogs.

31:30.360 --> 31:35.240
Only Lindstrom, the cook, stayed behind in Franheim.

31:37.740 --> 31:43.400
At first, everything went well. They went 28 kilometers on

31:43.400 --> 31:46.700
Saturday and 28 kilometers on Sunday.

31:47.720 --> 31:53.640
It was easy. Then, on Monday, the temperature went down

31:53.640 --> 31:56.920
to minus 56 degrees centigrade.

31:57.740 --> 32:02.640
There was white fog in front of their faces. They

32:02.640 --> 32:07.440
couldn't see anything, but they traveled 28

32:07.440 --> 32:14.480
kilometers. That night, in their tents, they nearly died of

32:14.480 --> 32:19.760
cold. Next day, they stopped and made snow

32:19.760 --> 32:26.520
houses. Inside the snow houses, it was warm. But everyone

32:26.520 --> 32:27.660
was unhappy.

32:28.880 --> 32:34.400
I told you, Ruweld, you Hansen said, even September is

32:34.400 --> 32:38.760
too early. We can't travel in this cold.

32:40.180 --> 32:44.720
Do you want us to die? Let's go back and

32:44.720 --> 32:46.280
wait for better weather.

32:48.120 --> 32:53.620
Amundsen was very angry. He was angry with Johansson, but

32:53.620 --> 32:55.160
he was angry with himself, too.

32:56.360 --> 32:58.720
He knew Johansson was right.

33:00.780 --> 33:06.120
All right, he said slowly. We can go on to

33:06.120 --> 33:08.280
the depot at 80 degrees south,

33:09.080 --> 33:14.280
leave the food there, and then go back. We can't

33:14.280 --> 33:15.180
do more than that.

33:17.180 --> 33:22.540
It was 37 kilometers to the depot. The wind was

33:22.540 --> 33:28.280
in their faces all day. Two dogs died on the

33:28.280 --> 33:28.500
way.

33:29.940 --> 33:34.800
At the depot, they did not stop. They put out

33:34.800 --> 33:39.920
the food and the flags, turned round and went north.

33:41.560 --> 33:45.620
At Glassed, the wind was behind them. The dogs ran

33:45.620 --> 33:48.500
quickly, and the men sat on the empty sledges.

33:49.120 --> 33:52.420
They went faster and faster. It was like a race.

33:53.640 --> 33:56.560
Amundsen was on Visting's sledge, and soon he,

33:57.060 --> 33:59.820
Visting and Hansen were three or four kilometers in front.

34:00.600 --> 34:04.400
Soon, they were alone. They traveled 75

34:04.400 --> 34:09.440
kilometers in nine hours, and they reached Framheim at four

34:09.440 --> 34:10.700
o'clock that afternoon.

34:13.120 --> 34:19.100
Vjorland arrived two hours later, with two more men. But

34:19.100 --> 34:21.420
the last two, Johansson and

34:21.420 --> 34:28.120
Prestrude, went more slowly. Their dogs were tired. Their feet

34:28.120 --> 34:31.360
were wet and cold. They had no food,

34:32.000 --> 34:37.720
and they were alone in the dark. The temperature was

34:37.720 --> 34:42.700
minus 51 degrees centigrade. They reached

34:42.700 --> 34:51.960
Framheim at midnight. Next morning, Johansson was angry. In front

34:51.960 --> 34:53.680
of everyone, he said,

34:54.400 --> 35:01.440
You were wrong, Ruhald. September was too early. I told

35:01.440 --> 35:04.120
you, but you didn't listen.

35:05.320 --> 35:09.960
And then you left us alone, and we nearly died

35:09.960 --> 35:16.300
in the cold. You're a bad captain. I'm a better

35:16.300 --> 35:23.940
captain than you are. Amundsen was very angry. But, at

35:23.940 --> 35:26.180
first, he said nothing,

35:27.140 --> 35:33.840
because he knew that Johansson was right. Then, that evening,

35:34.860 --> 35:36.760
he gave a letter to Johansson.

35:37.560 --> 35:42.420
It said, You aren't coming to the pole with me.

35:43.320 --> 35:47.440
When I go south, you can take some dogs and

35:47.440 --> 35:47.920
go east,

35:48.460 --> 35:52.200
took in Edward the Seventh Land. You can go with

35:52.200 --> 35:56.600
Prestrude and Stuberude. You can be the first men

35:56.600 --> 36:03.700
to go there, but not to the south pole. The

36:03.700 --> 36:06.460
Norwegians stayed in Framheim and waited.

36:07.480 --> 36:13.800
They lay in bed, listened to the wind outside, and

36:13.800 --> 36:17.260
thought about Scott and his motor sledges.

36:25.560 --> 36:29.540
Chapter 7. Motor sledges and mountains.

36:32.280 --> 36:36.700
Scott had two motor sledges now. They were the first

36:36.700 --> 36:38.320
motor sledges in the Antarctic,

36:39.200 --> 36:45.660
the first on Earth. On October 24, the motor sledges

36:45.660 --> 36:47.380
started south from Cape Evans.

36:48.940 --> 36:53.420
Four men went with them, but Scott stayed at Cape

36:53.420 --> 36:55.100
Evans for another week.

36:57.280 --> 37:04.180
Oats was unhappy. He wrote to his mother, We had

37:04.180 --> 37:08.260
a very bad winter here. I don't like Scott.

37:09.740 --> 37:13.580
We were here all winter, but he didn't learn to

37:13.580 --> 37:15.520
ski or to drive dogs.

37:17.200 --> 37:21.940
Our equipment is bad, and he doesn't think about other

37:21.940 --> 37:22.340
people.

37:24.260 --> 37:26.880
I'm going to sleep in his tent on the journey,

37:28.420 --> 37:29.420
but I don't want to.

37:33.000 --> 37:37.700
On November 1, Scott and Oats and six more men

37:37.700 --> 37:42.180
left Cape Evans with eight sledges and eight ponies.

37:43.880 --> 37:48.100
The ponies walked slowly because their feet went down into

37:48.100 --> 37:48.600
the snow.

37:49.300 --> 37:53.240
It was hard work for them, and they got tired

37:53.240 --> 37:54.040
very quickly.

37:55.680 --> 37:59.640
They traveled 13 or 14 kilometers in a day.

38:01.980 --> 38:06.760
Behind the ponies came miers with one sledge and some

38:06.760 --> 38:07.080
dogs.

38:08.500 --> 38:14.800
Miers knew how to drive dogs. Every day, miers started

38:14.800 --> 38:17.000
two hours after the ponies

38:17.730 --> 38:21.380
and arrived two hours before them.

38:23.770 --> 38:27.720
After five days, they found the motor sledges.

38:30.970 --> 38:36.760
The Norwegians began again on October 20. There were five

38:36.760 --> 38:37.700
men this time.

38:38.900 --> 38:45.900
Amundsen, Beorland, Visting, Harsell, and Hanssen.

38:47.420 --> 38:54.060
They had four sledges and 48 dogs. There was a

38:54.060 --> 38:55.380
lot of wind and fog.

38:57.230 --> 39:02.980
On the first day, Visting's sledge suddenly stopped, and the

39:02.980 --> 39:03.760
back went down.

39:04.780 --> 39:11.560
Come on, you dogs. He said angrily. Bull! Bull!

39:12.950 --> 39:19.540
At first, nothing happened. Then, slowly, the sledge moved again.

39:20.980 --> 39:25.720
Visting looked down over the side of the sledge. Under

39:25.720 --> 39:29.020
the snow, there was a 50-meter hole.

39:30.100 --> 39:36.060
Did you see that? Amundsen said. The ice wants to

39:36.060 --> 39:40.540
eat us. Men, dogs, sledges, everything.

39:43.000 --> 39:46.860
On the fourth day, they reached the depot at 80

39:46.860 --> 39:47.720
degrees south.

39:48.860 --> 39:52.660
There was a bad snowstorm, but they found the flags

39:52.660 --> 39:53.200
easily.

39:55.360 --> 39:59.360
Next day, the men stayed in their tents, and the

39:59.360 --> 40:01.560
dogs played in their holes under the snow.

40:02.920 --> 40:06.500
They were all happy. They had a lot of food.

40:07.240 --> 40:09.520
They had good equipment, and they were warm.

40:10.420 --> 40:11.540
They could travel fast.

40:14.080 --> 40:19.620
Next morning, the snowstorm stopped, and the journey began again.

40:22.140 --> 40:26.740
Today, everything is wonderful. The Orland wrote in his diary,

40:28.340 --> 40:33.060
but where is Scott, in front of us, or behind?

40:36.220 --> 40:40.300
There was no one with the motor sledges. They were

40:40.300 --> 40:43.600
broken. Scott looked at them angrily.

40:44.840 --> 40:50.280
It doesn't matter, he said. Teddy Evans and his men

40:50.280 --> 40:52.960
are in front of us. They're good men.

40:53.740 --> 40:58.420
They're pulling their sledges themselves. We can get to the

40:58.420 --> 40:59.840
pole on foot.

41:01.840 --> 41:06.640
Oats looked at meers. Oats and the ponies were tired,

41:07.420 --> 41:09.140
but meers and his dogs were not.

41:10.160 --> 41:12.000
The snow was home for them.

41:13.240 --> 41:19.260
That night, Oats wrote, three motor sledges at 1,000

41:19.260 --> 41:24.000
pounds each, 19 ponies at 5 pounds each,

41:25.240 --> 41:31.640
32 dogs at 1 pound 50 each. Well, it's not

41:31.640 --> 41:33.680
my money, it's Scott's.

41:35.340 --> 41:39.980
On November 21st, one of the ponies died.

41:42.460 --> 41:46.360
On November 11th, the Norwegians saw the mountains.

41:47.940 --> 41:52.160
The mountains were very high, some of the highest on

41:52.160 --> 41:54.840
earth. The Orland smiled.

41:55.860 --> 42:00.300
There is good skiing up there, Oald, he said. But

42:00.300 --> 42:01.780
can dogs get up there too?

42:02.780 --> 42:06.780
Of course they can, Amundsen said. Come on.

42:07.500 --> 42:12.260
They left Hanssen with the dogs, and skied a little

42:12.260 --> 42:13.100
way up the mountains.

42:14.140 --> 42:18.520
It was difficult, but the mountains were big and beautiful.

42:20.180 --> 42:24.260
Behind the mountains, Amundsen thought there was a high plateau

42:24.260 --> 42:25.140
of ice.

42:26.420 --> 42:31.940
That's it, Amundsen said. That's the road to the pole.

42:33.020 --> 42:36.360
Tomorrow, we can bring the dogs and sledges up here.

42:37.320 --> 42:42.280
But now, let's have a ski race. Who can get

42:42.280 --> 42:43.640
back to camp first?

42:45.000 --> 42:48.620
They laughed, and skied happily down the white snow.

42:50.020 --> 42:54.620
This is like home, Beorland thought, but it's bigger than

42:54.620 --> 42:56.300
Norway and better.

42:58.620 --> 43:02.480
In the next four days, the dogs pulled the sledges

43:02.480 --> 43:03.700
81 kilometers

43:03.700 --> 43:06.980
and went up 3,000 meters.

43:08.660 --> 43:13.840
At last, Amundsen and Beorland stood on the plateau behind

43:13.840 --> 43:14.320
the mountains.

43:15.260 --> 43:17.880
They were tired, happy men.

43:19.400 --> 43:21.660
Beorland looked back at the mountains.

43:23.000 --> 43:26.560
Can a motor sledge get up here? He asked.

43:28.080 --> 43:29.320
Amundsen smiled.

43:30.460 --> 43:34.280
No, he said. I don't think so.

43:35.360 --> 43:39.840
And Scott doesn't like dogs, so his men are going

43:39.840 --> 43:43.060
to pull their sledges up these mountains themselves.

43:44.260 --> 43:46.060
Would you like to do that, Ulaf?

43:47.520 --> 43:49.040
Beorland didn't answer.

43:49.760 --> 43:54.020
He smiled and skied happily away across the snow.

44:02.680 --> 44:03.400
The

44:03.400 --> 44:06.420
Chapter 8 Across the Plateau

44:08.620 --> 44:12.780
On November 21st, the Norwegians killed 30 dogs.

44:14.040 --> 44:18.120
They were happy, Amundsen said, and now they're going to

44:18.120 --> 44:18.540
die quickly.

44:19.480 --> 44:23.780
We need three sledges and 18 dogs to go to

44:23.780 --> 44:24.080
the pole.

44:25.480 --> 44:29.000
When the dogs were dead, the other dogs ate them.

44:29.920 --> 44:31.420
The men ate them, too.

44:33.160 --> 44:36.080
They were good friends, Beorland wrote in his diary.

44:37.360 --> 44:39.020
And now they are good food.

44:41.020 --> 44:43.560
Two days later, the dogs were fat.

44:45.340 --> 44:49.380
Then, in the snowstorm, they began their journey again.

44:50.540 --> 44:53.220
After the snowstorm, there was fog.

44:54.300 --> 44:57.120
And in the fog, they got lost on an ice

44:57.120 --> 44:59.440
river with hundreds of big holes in it.

45:00.640 --> 45:04.380
They could see nothing, and it was very dangerous.

45:05.860 --> 45:09.360
In four days, they moved nine kilometers.

45:11.100 --> 45:14.720
But the ice is beautiful, Beorland wrote.

45:15.660 --> 45:17.860
Blue and green and white.

45:18.600 --> 45:23.240
This is a wonderful place, but I don't want to

45:23.240 --> 45:24.240
stay a long time.

45:26.600 --> 45:30.780
After the ice, there were strong winds and bad snowstorms.

45:31.820 --> 45:34.080
They could see nothing in front of them.

45:35.200 --> 45:39.580
But every day, they traveled 25 or 30 kilometers.

45:41.080 --> 45:45.420
Then, on December 9th, the sun came out.

45:45.420 --> 45:53.580
They were at 88 degrees, 23 minutes south, 175 kilometers

45:53.580 --> 45:54.900
from the pole.

45:57.080 --> 46:00.060
Five more long days, Beorland wrote.

46:01.180 --> 46:04.280
That's all now. But where is Scott?

46:07.800 --> 46:11.660
For four days, Scott's men stayed in their tents near

46:11.660 --> 46:12.080
the mountains.

46:13.980 --> 46:17.460
There is a bad snowstorm outside, Oates wrote.

46:18.420 --> 46:21.860
It's too cold for the ponies, and our clothes and

46:21.860 --> 46:23.180
skis are bad too.

46:25.540 --> 46:28.520
On December 9th, Oates killed the ponies.

46:29.600 --> 46:32.800
They were tired and ill, and they could not walk

46:32.800 --> 46:33.560
up to the plateau.

46:35.320 --> 46:38.080
Their mirrors and his dogs went back to Cape Evans.

46:39.680 --> 46:42.920
We can pull the sledges ourselves, Scott said.

46:43.620 --> 46:46.560
We can do it. We're all strong men.

46:48.520 --> 46:51.040
There were two sledges and eight men.

46:52.080 --> 46:54.440
They went 24 kilometers a day.

46:55.940 --> 47:00.940
On December 31st, Scott said to Teddy Evans and the

47:00.940 --> 47:02.020
men on the second sledge,

47:03.080 --> 47:05.820
You can't ski well. Leave your skis here.

47:06.660 --> 47:11.440
So they pulled their sledge 24 kilometers without skis.

47:12.720 --> 47:16.180
Next day, Scott went to Teddy Evans' tent.

47:17.500 --> 47:21.760
You're ill, Teddy, he said. You can't come to the

47:21.760 --> 47:21.960
pole.

47:23.220 --> 47:25.700
Take two men and go back, tomorrow.

47:27.420 --> 47:29.320
Teddy Evans was very unhappy.

47:30.720 --> 47:33.080
Two men, Captain, he said.

47:34.020 --> 47:35.280
Why not three?

47:36.280 --> 47:40.120
Because Bowers is going to come with me, Scott said.

47:40.800 --> 47:42.660
Be strong. We need him.

47:44.040 --> 47:47.240
But you have food on your sledge for four men,

47:47.620 --> 47:49.560
not five, Evans said.

47:51.140 --> 47:52.620
And Bowers has no skis.

47:54.160 --> 47:57.100
I'm the captain, Teddy, Scott said.

47:57.640 --> 47:59.460
You do what I say.

47:59.460 --> 48:03.140
Take two men and leave Bowers with me.

48:04.680 --> 48:06.220
Oats wrote to his mother.

48:07.720 --> 48:09.360
I'm going to the pole with Scott.

48:10.320 --> 48:12.520
I am pleased and I feel strong.

48:13.720 --> 48:15.900
But in his diary, he wrote,

48:17.300 --> 48:19.080
My feet are very bad.

48:19.920 --> 48:24.080
They are always wet now, and they don't look good.

48:26.540 --> 48:31.360
On January 4th, Scott's man left Teddy Evans and went

48:31.360 --> 48:31.620
on.

48:32.700 --> 48:39.080
Scott, Oats, Wilson, and Edgar Evans had skis, but Bowers

48:39.080 --> 48:39.640
did not.

48:40.980 --> 48:43.760
They were 270 kilometers from the pole.

48:47.820 --> 48:52.160
December 14th, 1911 was a warm, sunny day.

48:53.160 --> 48:56.680
Five Norwegians skied over the beautiful white snow.

48:58.220 --> 48:59.280
It was very quiet.

49:00.340 --> 49:01.140
No one spoke.

49:02.240 --> 49:04.480
They were excited and happy.

49:05.660 --> 49:08.980
Six more kilometers, Biorland thought.

49:09.940 --> 49:11.500
Is there a British flag?

49:12.320 --> 49:14.830
I can't see a flag, but...

49:15.420 --> 49:17.480
Look, Harsel said.

49:18.100 --> 49:19.660
What's that over there?

49:20.880 --> 49:24.200
Biorland left his sledge and see quickly a way over

49:24.200 --> 49:24.580
the snow.

49:25.680 --> 49:26.580
What is it?

49:27.020 --> 49:27.240
He thought.

49:28.000 --> 49:28.300
Is it?

49:29.020 --> 49:29.620
No.

49:30.960 --> 49:32.800
It's nothing, he called.

49:33.560 --> 49:34.860
There's nothing there.

49:35.840 --> 49:36.440
Nothing.

49:38.320 --> 49:40.580
Three kilometers, two.

49:42.000 --> 49:42.600
Rewald!

49:43.420 --> 49:44.760
Hansen called to Amundsen.

49:45.600 --> 49:47.060
Go in front of me, please.

49:47.880 --> 49:48.860
It helps my dogs.

49:50.380 --> 49:52.900
That's not true, Biorland thought.

49:53.720 --> 49:55.480
His dogs are running well today.

49:56.640 --> 49:58.980
But Hansen wants Amundsen to be first.

49:59.800 --> 50:02.500
The first man at the South Pole.

50:03.980 --> 50:08.140
They skied on and on, over the beautiful snow.

50:10.520 --> 50:12.300
Stop, Amundsen said.

50:13.680 --> 50:15.420
He waited quietly for his men.

50:15.420 --> 50:20.780
And this is it, he said.

50:22.020 --> 50:23.460
Biorland looked at him.

50:24.460 --> 50:26.660
But there's nothing here, he said.

50:27.840 --> 50:28.920
Amundsen smiled.

50:29.920 --> 50:32.840
Oh, yes, there is, he said.

50:33.560 --> 50:37.200
There's something very important here, Ulaf.

50:37.980 --> 50:40.240
Very, very important.

50:41.940 --> 50:43.100
What's that draw up?

50:44.060 --> 50:47.240
Us, we are here now.

50:47.940 --> 50:49.900
Isn't that important, Ulaf?

50:51.300 --> 50:55.220
The four men stood on the snow and looked at

50:55.220 --> 50:55.440
him.

50:56.880 --> 51:02.240
Then, slowly, they all began to laugh.

51:11.060 --> 51:14.920
Chapter 9, the End of the Race

51:16.920 --> 51:20.480
The Norwegians stayed two days at the Pole.

51:22.000 --> 51:25.460
They left a tent there with a Norwegian flag on

51:25.460 --> 51:25.620
it.

51:26.800 --> 51:30.620
Inside the tent, they left some food, a letter for

51:30.620 --> 51:31.280
the King of Norway,

51:32.240 --> 51:33.260
and a letter for Scott.

51:35.140 --> 51:38.540
They left some more black flags near the Pole and

51:38.540 --> 51:40.340
one 28 kilometers north.

51:41.780 --> 51:45.320
Then they skied away, back to the north.

51:47.340 --> 51:50.460
It's a beautiful day, Biorland wrote.

51:51.440 --> 51:54.020
The sun is warm, the snow is good.

51:55.000 --> 51:58.160
But the dogs run too quickly, I can't get in

51:58.160 --> 51:58.740
front of them.

52:00.060 --> 52:02.080
They found their depots easily.

52:03.440 --> 52:05.600
There were ten between the Pole and Framheim.

52:06.600 --> 52:09.080
Each depot had a lot of food.

52:10.320 --> 52:12.960
They laughed and skied quickly down the mountains.

52:14.220 --> 52:17.540
Often, they skied 50 kilometers a day.

52:18.900 --> 52:26.340
On Friday, January 26, 1912, they came back to Framheim.

52:27.300 --> 52:29.360
It was four o'clock in the morning.

52:30.940 --> 52:35.340
Inside the wooden house, Lindstrom, the cook, was asleep.

52:36.920 --> 52:38.940
Amundsen walked quietly to his bed.

52:40.180 --> 52:43.240
Good morning, Lindstrom, he said.

52:44.240 --> 52:45.160
He's our coffee, ready?

52:48.680 --> 52:51.200
The black flags waited at the Pole.

52:53.060 --> 52:54.380
What's that, Captain?

52:55.240 --> 52:57.320
Bower said, over there.

52:58.660 --> 52:59.280
Where?

53:00.020 --> 53:01.400
Scott asked, what?

53:02.460 --> 53:04.120
Oh, my God.

53:05.420 --> 53:09.160
They all saw the small black flag in the snow,

53:10.020 --> 53:12.680
two kilometers in front of them.

53:13.960 --> 53:17.600
Slowly, they pulled their sledge to it.

53:19.300 --> 53:25.840
Next day, January 17th, 1912, they found the tent and

53:25.840 --> 53:27.240
the Norwegian flag.

53:29.020 --> 53:32.740
Near it, Scott took the British flag from under his

53:32.740 --> 53:34.640
clothes and put it up.

53:36.040 --> 53:38.080
In his diary, Scott wrote,

53:39.820 --> 53:42.620
This is a very bad day.

53:43.860 --> 53:47.420
We're all tired and have cold feet.

53:47.600 --> 53:52.360
And hands, which is minus 30 degrees centigrade.

53:53.440 --> 53:55.380
And there is a snowstorm.

53:57.520 --> 54:02.660
Great God, this is an awful place.

54:05.400 --> 54:12.640
They turned north, five tired, unhappy men, in the coldest,

54:13.360 --> 54:15.940
emptiest place on earth.

54:18.780 --> 54:26.240
On March 13th, 1912, Scott's wife, Kathleen, looked at her

54:26.240 --> 54:26.980
morning newspaper.

54:28.940 --> 54:32.940
Norway's flag at South Pole, it said.

54:34.660 --> 54:38.300
She looked at it for a long time and then

54:38.300 --> 54:39.120
began to cry.

54:41.180 --> 54:43.640
What's the matter, her friend asked.

54:45.100 --> 54:49.120
My poor, poor husband, Mrs. Scott said.

54:50.440 --> 54:51.700
What's happened to him?

54:52.860 --> 54:54.220
Where is he now?

54:57.360 --> 54:59.220
Scott's men were always hungry.

54:59.980 --> 55:02.900
There were not many depots and they were difficult to

55:02.900 --> 55:03.160
find.

55:04.260 --> 55:08.420
We need to find the next depot today, Oates wrote.

55:09.500 --> 55:13.500
But how can we find one black flag in all

55:13.500 --> 55:14.300
this snow?

55:15.220 --> 55:16.640
It's very difficult.

55:17.880 --> 55:21.900
And there is food for four men, not five.

55:23.860 --> 55:26.320
They were all tired and ill too.

55:27.700 --> 55:31.500
Oates's feet were black now and he could not feel

55:31.500 --> 55:31.760
them.

55:33.540 --> 55:37.320
On February 16th, Edgar Evans died.

55:39.120 --> 55:42.080
On the 17th, they were past the mountains.

55:43.540 --> 55:46.420
At the depot there, they ate one of the dead

55:46.420 --> 55:46.700
ponies.

55:48.260 --> 55:54.460
Then they went on, 10, 11, 12 kilometers a day.

55:55.840 --> 55:59.540
They were ill because their clothes were not warm and

55:59.540 --> 56:00.740
they didn't have much food.

56:02.020 --> 56:06.720
The temperature was sometimes minus 40 degrees centigrade.

56:08.080 --> 56:12.000
On March 7th, Scott looked at Oates's feet.

56:12.820 --> 56:14.460
They were big and black.

56:15.880 --> 56:19.480
I can't pull the sledge now, Oates said.

56:20.260 --> 56:22.000
It's very difficult to walk.

56:23.180 --> 56:25.720
Am I going to lose these feet, Captain?

56:27.500 --> 56:32.320
Scott looked at Oates's feet and said nothing.

56:34.540 --> 56:39.280
On March 9th, they found another depot, but there was

56:39.280 --> 56:40.000
not much food.

56:41.140 --> 56:43.440
Slowly, they walked on.

56:44.880 --> 56:47.260
Oates's feet were worse every day.

56:50.200 --> 56:52.340
March 17th was Oates's birthday.

56:53.820 --> 56:54.560
He was 32.

56:56.420 --> 56:59.520
He lay in the tent and listened to the wind

56:59.520 --> 56:59.860
outside.

56:59.860 --> 57:07.180
He was very cold, very hungry, and very, very tired.

57:09.800 --> 57:13.180
He wrote a letter to his mother and gave it

57:13.180 --> 57:13.480
to Wilson.

57:15.080 --> 57:18.420
Then he got up and opened the door of the

57:18.420 --> 57:18.600
tent.

57:20.220 --> 57:22.200
He stopped in the door for a minute.

57:23.520 --> 57:26.620
Scott, Wilson, and Bowers looked at him.

57:27.640 --> 57:28.640
They didn't speak.

57:30.700 --> 57:33.900
I'm going outside for a minute, Oates said.

57:35.160 --> 57:36.220
And maybe sometime.

57:38.740 --> 57:40.580
They didn't see him again.

57:44.360 --> 57:47.320
At Cape Evans, the Englishman waited.

57:49.140 --> 57:52.220
On December 11th, Mears and the Dogs came back.

57:53.660 --> 57:58.020
On January 3rd, Teddy Evans and his two men arrived

57:58.020 --> 57:58.900
at Cape Evans.

58:00.300 --> 58:03.140
The Terranova came and went.

58:04.920 --> 58:05.200
Winter began.

58:06.620 --> 58:08.340
Scott did not come.

58:10.960 --> 58:13.420
The Englishman waited all winter at Cape Evans.

58:14.980 --> 58:20.760
Then on October 26th, 1912, they started for the South.

58:22.820 --> 58:25.420
Two weeks later, they found a tent.

58:26.800 --> 58:28.760
There were three bodies in the tent.

58:30.080 --> 58:32.900
Scott, Wilson, and Bowers.

58:34.780 --> 58:36.940
They put the bodies under the snow.

58:38.400 --> 58:40.800
Then they took the men's letters and diaries

58:41.290 --> 58:43.220
and went north to Cape Evans again.

58:45.360 --> 58:47.480
In Scott's diary, they read,

58:49.460 --> 58:50.980
Oates died like a good Englishman.

58:51.800 --> 58:52.800
We all did.

58:54.420 --> 58:58.400
Please remember us and look after our families.

58:59.860 --> 59:01.480
We did our best.

59:04.460 --> 59:06.080
No one found Oates's body.

59:07.400 --> 59:12.000
But he is there somewhere under the snow and the

59:12.000 --> 59:12.200
wind

59:13.120 --> 59:17.280
in the coldest, emptiest place on Earth.

